<font color="#FF0000">REAR ECHELON PERSONELL (REMFS)</font><br>
<tt>Mon Aug 18  2:34:49 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
U.S.A.F. = REMF?<br>
Dear Friends,<br>
I'm relatively new to the internet and just found this site. The ³REMF² thread really hit home since I have felt much guilt over this for years. Back in 1972 I had a lottery number of around 360 and no worry of being drafted. Yet, I WANTED to do my part. There was no question of where I should go - I loved aircraft so the Air Force was where it had to be. Besides, I¹m honest enough to know my limitations and, since I¹d always been much more into reading than facing physical challenges, I knew I was unlikely to ³cut it² in any other branch of the service. (No SEAL wannabe here!) I joined upon graduation and was sent to the 301st Squadron of Strategic Air Command at Lockbourne Air Force Base near Columbus, OH (renamed ³Rickenbacker AFB² the day after I was discharged). Since I¹d heard for five years that the war would be over ³any day now² I (in my ignorance) had no reason to think it wouldn¹t last another five and at the first opportunity volunteered to go anywhere in SEA the Air Force was willing to send me. As it turned out, my unit had been stationed at Anderson AFB (Guam) and/or Utapeo (Thailand) for years, personnel being sent on a TDY basis so that many ended up being there for three (or more) years out of their four year enlistment. My wish to ³do my share² was suddenly answered in December when we were ordered to leave immediately for Clark AFB (Philippine Islands). We went there and took part in Linebacker II, the final air assault on North Vietnam that ended the war. I also got my wish to see ³The ŒNam² when our plane broke down and a layover at DaNang Air Base was called for. In a little over two days I experienced 98% boredom (not to mention a lot of paranoia - there wasn¹t many Americans around by that time) and 2% sheer terror during a mortar attack (or rockets or who the hell knows what - the USAF never prepared us for or explained these things in basic training, so I had no idea what was happening - which scared the shit out of me all that much more). A friend I made there was blown away during the attack, which I have felt guilty about ever since (to this day I don¹t know if he survived or not). And even someone as naive as myself could in short order see that our ³peace with honor² was a sham. Goodbye innocence, goodbye belief in ³the system², hello cynicism. <br>
I never told anyone about this when we flew back to Clark, or to anyone at Lockbourne where I thought we¹d be welcomed home. Fat chance - the general feeling was that we¹d just come back from ³vacation² and those we had left behind resented having had ³to do our work for us.² Excuse me for living! Later that year I stood by helplessly on the flightline as the crew of a KC-135A Stratotanker (refueling plane) burned to death after the wing of another 135 struck it while taxying during an alert exercise. Like my friend months earlier, I could do nothing but stand by in terror and do nothing. The smell of burning flesh is something I¹ll never forget. Meanwhile I, like all the rest of you, experienced the same anti-Vet hostility every time I went off base (civvies did no good - the short haircut was like a neon sign in those days). My career ended when the Air Force, suddenly realizing it had a surplus of airmen no longer needed now that the war was over, began throwing people out left and right for petty bullshit - myself included. I had an honorable discharge but I NEVER WANTED OUT in the first place. The one thing that gave me a purpose to live, even after what I¹d seen in ŒNam, was to serve my country. Now I had one more thing to be ashamed of on top of being a vet (it didn¹t matter where you served or what you did we were all tossed into the same barrel). I then began 10 years of self-destructive behavior that cost me my first marriage and what few jobs I could find. Finally I got my act together, went to college, started a retail company from scratch that became very successful, and married a lady who loves me very much and has stuck with me through thick and thin. End of story? Hardly.<br>
Right before we married the nightmares began, followed by an occasional flashback to the men and their burning flesh or the incoming mortar rounds and a dead (?) buddy. I began to go from violent moods to utter despair - with nothing in between. I had PTSD, a term I wasn¹t even familiar with. Even after learning what was happening I refused to get help at a nearby Vet Center. Who was I to enter a place used by brave men and women who had made such great sacrifices for their country? I was a nothing, an Air Force REMF - and a rejected one at that. I refused to go until I came close to killing others while in a blind rage. I was ashamed to enter the place but did so for my wife¹s sake. It was there that I learned that I was a ³Vietnam Era² veteran - not a REAL Vet - a bit of news that hit me like shrapnel through the heart. I received help but my time there ended after a couple months in a rap group. The others, all ground-pounding, jungle-eating grunts who once ruled the Earth, agreed that I was part of the group even if I was only in-country two days (which, by the way, I cannot prove as there is no documentation - you don¹t get paperwork for an emergency landing - putting me in the ³wannabe² category according to some).<br>
As time went by it was obvious that they were part of an inner circle of which I had not earned the right to be included - which is why I didn¹t want to go there in the first place. This message became clear without their having to speak the words. I left never to return. Although, after two suicide attempts requiring hospitalization, I started seeing a psychiatrist on a regular basis and became somewhat better, during this past year everything has gone straight downhill. I¹ll be honest, I hated the 1980¹s and hate the Œ90¹s even worse. What happened to honor and integrity? As a bumper sticker I read said, this country is the only place where a homeless combat vet can sleep in a cardboard box while a draft dodger can sleep in the White House. The 1960¹s and early Œ70¹s, when men and women stood up for what they believed in - right or wrong - was far better than the limp-dicked, wishy-washy, middle-ground politically-correct society we live in today. I HATE THIS FUCKING PLACE! While overseas I can¹t believe anyone ever talked about getting back to ³The World² because The World sucks as far as I¹m concerned. Because of these feelings, ever since the rap group ³fall out² in Jan. 1991 I¹ve steadily withdrawn from the world, moved my office from my warehouse to my home nearly seven years ago and have rarely ever stepped outside again among the people who called us ³baby killers² or the ones who said nothing (if you¹re not part of the cure you¹re part of the problem, so both are equally guilty), or the ones who spent months giving parades and benefits for our weekend-warrior comrades who stormed the desert. No disrespect for their efforts is meant (I¹m proud of them all) but I nearly bit my tongue off after hearing for the 100th time that ³this parade is for the Vietnam Vets too². Well FUCK YOU VERY MUCH. Where were you 25 years ago, asshole? I never asked for a goddamn parade but never realized I¹d have to listen to 20 years worth of crap about ³drug-crazed, criminal, psychopathic baby-killing Vietnam Vets.² America, do you think you can make up for twenty years of abuse now with a few parades? Hell no, the damage is already done.<br>
I don¹t want to make anyone reading this upset, nor do I want to start a flame (which I¹m emotionally unable to handle right now), but I hate this country, I hate the government and I hate the military. Screw them all. I hate them not just for my pain but for the pain of every man and woman endured who served in ŒNam. Because even today the assholes we live among don¹t want to hear about it and rather we¹d go away and be forgotten. One of the reasons I WON¹T put Vietnam behind me (as if I could!) is because I refuse to let THEM forget the sacrifices so many made only to have society say it was ³all for nothing² and that we were (and still are) ³losers.² I am a living, breathing monument to what Vietnam did to my generation and the candle will burn until there¹s nothing left. I am not only emotionally disabled, but after years of taking antidepressant drugs (all at MY expense, no VA handouts) I am also physically disabled.<br>
The ultimate irony of this is that after almost 25 years of pain I still cannot call myself a Vietnam Vet. I¹ve paid the price but have no proof, putting me in the ³wannabe² category. But even if I had proof then I¹d fall into the ³REMF² category - and would still have to be ashamed. In the past ten years many Vets have started to feel good about their service, but I still don¹t count as I¹m not a ³real² vet. Recently I wrote for some catalogs hoping to buy a shirt, patch or something to make myself feel better about my time in the Air Force. Guess what? Once again I¹m shit out of luck. If you served in the USAF virtually nothing is available, so I guess what we did counted for nothing.  I bought an expensive book on SAC but it didn¹t mention my my base or my outfit (the world¹s first all-jet refueling squadron). Another book on KC-135 history ignores us as well. A book on Linebacker operations spent about one page out of 300 explaining how the KC-135s made most combat flights over the north possible (as well as our having saved a lot of planes and pilots), and B-52 missions ANYWHERE possible. One whole page is all we were worth. Did anyone benefit from those Arc-Light missions? How about the Marines at Khe Sahn? Without the Œ135 it would have been impossible. Yet who cares? Even within the Air Force the Œ135 is ignored, the spotlight always being shined on fighters, bombers or Œcopters. <br>
This made me so angry that I had my computer hooked up to the internet. After many years of isolation (no TV, radio or newspapers) I learned that my beautiful base had been sold to civilians and bulldozed in the name of progress. My aircraft, the KC-135A, is no longer in service. Strategic Air Command had been dismantled. Clark AFB was abandoned due to a volcanic eruption, but this was a mere convenience for ³Slick Willy² Clinton who gave away Subic Bay as well. I spent hundreds of hours on the Net and came up with a grand total of less than ONE PAGE describing my base and squadron. Otherwise, all the lives given (both at Lockbourne due to a number of accidents, or in SEA), all the dedication and sacrifice (you may recall that for over 30 years SAC was our first line of defense), all the duty and honor meant absolutely fucking nothing. All forgotten, tossed on the scrap heap, swept under the rug. Now I not only ³lost² in Vietnam but I lost at home too! What the hell was it all for?!<br>
Other than some photos I took overseas and at Lockbourne, I¹ve now lost any remaining evidence of my duty, my pride in a job well done, and of (pardon the expression) going above and beyond what was expected of me, except for discharge papers more or less saying ³good riddance, chump.² The jerks protesting at the airports were right. It really was all for nothing since both our society and our government have dedicated themselves to removing all evidence that we ever did anything (at least in my case).<br>
 I¹m posting this overly-long letter not because I want sympathy, pity or a hand-out, but because I am pleading for help. My last remaining bit of pride and dignity have been stolen by the merciless bastards in Washington and it was the only thing left keeping me alive. I am hoping that someone on this board can can offer an alternative other than the only one I can think of, which is to permanently exit this madhouse of a world. Even though I¹m classified by others as a ³REMF and a wannabee² I can tell you that I¹m in a world of hurt. I dearly love and respect everyone who did their share and have felt guilty for years that I didn¹t have the opportunity to contribute more than I did. But as much as I wish that everyone who was in-country could have made it back alive and well, I often feel that those who didn¹t survive were better off as they avoided the War at Home. As for myself, I¹d infinitely rather be with them than in this godforsaken nightmare of a place.<br><br>
Just another casualty,<br>
Bill Anchors<br>
